<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-10-12T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-10-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="29" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d29">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/560.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-10-12">
                                    <hi rend="italic">October 12, 1911</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The rebellion appears well organized and well directed. The whole of the
                            new army forces at Wuchang, about 15,000 men and comprising three army
                            corps, have joined the revolution, The rebellion is undoubtedly the most
                            serious since the Taiping. Thus far foreign interests have been
                            carefully respected.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Williams.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>